 from pom anke imsd uni mainz de prof dr klaus pommerening subject summary des init vector as additional key keywords des key search initialisation vector nntp posting host anke imsd uni mainz de organization johannes gutenberg universitaet mainz lines six zero at the risk of getting lost in the clipper chip discussion i give a summary on my recent question in article i wrote the recent discussion in this news group suggests that a key search attack against des is quite feasible now but normally des is applied in cbc or cfb mode where one chooses a random init vector of eight bytes questions makes it sense to handle the init vector as an additional key then we have a five six six four one two zero bit key if yes is anything known about the security of this key scheme can we break it faster than by exhaustive search through the one two zero bit key space unfortunately the answer is no concealing the initialisation vector essentially doesn t give any additional security i got three answers from grady netcom com mark lomas cl cam ac uk smb research att com that opened my eyes it s pretty simple say e is encryption and d decryption with key k on six four bit blocks let c zero be the initialisation vector m one m two the message blocks c one c two the cipher text blocks then encryption in cipher block chaining cbc mode works by the formula ci e mi xor ci one and decryption by mi ci one xor d ci so if the attacker doesn t have c zero this only affects the first message block m one but she can do her key search attack on m two m three the situation in cipher feedback cfb mode is a bit more complicated but similar and left as an exercise for the reader finally there is the modified output feedback mode ofb where des or whatever block cipher you use simply acts as random generator by si e si one with initialisation vector seed s zero and encryption is given by ci mi xor si here the usual known plaintext attack against xor bitstream ciphers reduces the cracking to key search 